		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Neil Postman</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>Neil Postman</b> (<a href="/wiki/March_8" title="March 8">March 8</a>, <a href="/wiki/1931" title="1931">1931</a> - <a href="/wiki/October_5" title="October 5">October 5</a>, <a href="/wiki/2003" title="2003">2003</a>) was an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Author" title="Author">author</a>, <a href="/wiki/Media_theory" title="Media theory" class="mw-redirect">media theorist</a> and <a href="/wiki/Cultural_critic" title="Cultural critic">cultural critic</a>, who is best known by the general public for his 1985 book about television, <i><a href="/wiki/Amusing_Ourselves_to_Death" title="Amusing Ourselves to Death">Amusing Ourselves to Death</a></i>. For more than forty years, he was associated with <a href="/wiki/New_York_University" title="New York University">New York University</a>. Postman was a <a href="/wiki/Humanist" title="Humanist">humanist</a>, who believed that "there is a limit to the promise of new technology, and that it cannot be a substitute for human values." <sup id="cite_ref-news_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-news-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
