<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Neil_Postman&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: References">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">References</span></h2>
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-news-0">^ <a href="#cite_ref-news_0-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-news_0-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-news_0-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="http://www.pbs.org/newshour/forum/january96/postman_1-17.html" class="external text" title="http://www.pbs.org/newshour/forum/january96/postman_1-17.html" rel="nofollow">PBS Newshour Interview, 1996</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> (Postman, 1992. p.51)</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> from <i>The Disappearance of Childhood</i></li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.mat.upm.es/~jcm/postman-informing.html" class="external text" title="http://www.mat.upm.es/~jcm/postman-informing.html" rel="nofollow">Talk given at the German Informatics Society (Gesellschaft fuer Informatik) on October 11, 1990 in Stuttgart.</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.frostbytes.com/~jimf/informing.html" class="external text" title="http://www.frostbytes.com/~jimf/informing.html" rel="nofollow">"Informing Ourselves to Death" (1990)</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-5"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5" title="">^</a></b> from the Neil Postman book "Amusing Ourselves To Death"</li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> from the Neil Postman book "Amusing Ourselves To Death"</li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7" title="">^</a></b> "Language Education in a Knowledge Context", 32.</li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> In <a href="http://criticalsnips.wordpress.com/2007/07/22/neil-postman-bullshit-and-the-art-of-crap-detection/" class="external text" title="http://criticalsnips.wordpress.com/2007/07/22/neil-postman-bullshit-and-the-art-of-crap-detection/" rel="nofollow">this speech</a>, Postman encouraged teachers to help their students "distinguish useful talk from bullshit". He argued that it was the most important skill students could learn, and that teaching it would help students understand their own values and beliefs.</li>
</ol>
